==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scull
<hw>Scull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Of uncertain origin; cf. Icel.
<ets>skola</ets> to wash.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A boat; a cockboat. See <er>Sculler</er>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of a pair of short oars worked by one
person.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A single oar used at the stern in
propelling a boat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The common skua gull.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Scull
<hw>Scull</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sculled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sculling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To impel (a
boat) with a pair of sculls, or with a single scull or oar worked over
the stern obliquely from side to side.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scull</ent>⟦br⟧

